NBA Box Score Analysis

- How have NBA offenses changed over the past 20 years? How is scoring up so much?¶

- Which team stats correlate most to winning games, and how has that changed team strategy?¶

- How have the players themselves changed, both in their role and physically?¶

- What are some exemplary teams and players that define this change?¶

Scoring

Easily the most apparent change over the past 20 seasons is the huge jump in per game scoring.¶

  • Average scoring for the 2004-2005 season was just 97.2 points per game.

  • Scoring rose to over 114 points per game for the last two seasons, an increase of 17 ppg, or 17.5%!

  • Increase in scoring accelerated over the last decade (2014 - 2024) after only increasing slightly from 2004 - 2014

  • Low in scoring occured in the lockout shortened 2011 - 2012 season (96.3 ppg), however this could be an outlier due to the difficulty of scoring in a compressed season with little rest and a short training camp.

How has scoring increased?

Are teams just playing quicker and taking more shots?¶

  • Total shot attempts have risen steadily and significantly over the years

  • 80.3 FGA per game in 2004, rising to 88.9 FGA, an increase of 8.6 shots per game, or about 10%

  • This does not fully explain 17% increase in scoring.

  • In addition, free throws made per game, which are points scored without adding to the field goal attempt totals, are down from 19.7 in 04-05 to 17.0 in 23-24

So where are the extra points coming from?¶

Team Shot 'Diet'

Three point attempts vs. Two point attempts¶

  • Teams have gone from 64.6 two point attempts per game down to only 53.8.

  • Three point attempts have more than doubled, from 15.8 attempts to over 35.1 per game.

  • Three pointers as a percent of total shots has gone from only 19.6% up to 39.5%

Better Shooting

2 Point Percentage up from .470 to .545¶

  • Increase of 16%!

3 Point Percentage up from .355 to .365¶

  • Not as much of an increase, but on more than twice as many attempts. Volume of shots increased, presumably meaning that teams were less selective in which 3 point shots to take. Even with a higher volume, the percentage of makes still went up.

Overall Shooting Percentage up from .448 to .474¶

Efficiency

For the last 12 years, NBA offenses have generated more and more shots per field goal attempt:¶

  • Offenses hit a low of 1.182 points per FGA in 2012-13
  • Efficiency hit a high of 1.299 points per FGA in 2022-23
  • Combined with the increase in total shot attempts, this explains the 17% total increase in scoring

Efficiency --> Winning

Unsurprisingly, offensive efficiency (PTS/FGA) is highly correlated with winning¶

  • For most years from 2002-2024, efficiency more correlated with winning than total points scored
  • It is significantly more correlated to winning than total shots made (FG)
  • Teams with an efficiency more than 0.05 above league average have won 65.4% of their games, equivalent to a 53 win season
Win% Teams With Efficiency Above League Average: 0.582
Win% Teams With Efficiency of 0.05 or more Above League Average: 0.654
Win% Teams With Efficiency of 0.075 Above League Average: 0.696

The Chase for Efficiency

When we look at shot selection through the eyes of efficiency, we see how and why NBA offensive strategy has changed:¶

  • PTS/2FGA (two point efficiency) was for a long time much lower than PTS/3FGA (three point efficiency)
  • Chasing efficiency, 2FGA were traded for more valuable 3FGA
  • With teams more selective in their 2FGA, two point efficiency increased.
  • In last few years the difference has vanished, and now each shot is equally efficient, suggesting that the current shot diet is the one which gives optimal efficiency

Team Recap

  • NBA Offensive Pace has increased, with teams now avaraging 10% more shots
  • In an effort to gain efficiency, which drives wins, teams have traded some less efficient 2 Point attempts for 3 Point attempts
  • Overall points per field goal attempt has increased from around 1.2 a decade ago to close to 1.3 today
  • Evolution largely begins in 2011-12 season and has continued to the present

Player Evolution 2011-2024

How have players changed in conjunction with the shift in offensive strategy?¶

  • Who is shooting all these 3s?
  • How are positional roles changing or evolving?
  • How are players changing physically with a faster pace of play and more floor spacing?

3 Point Shooting

Who is shooting all the 3s? Everyone¶

  • In 11-12 season, 101 players with 15+ games played averaged three 3FGA or more. By 23-24, 224 players did.
  • In 11-12 season, 17 players averaged 5 threes taken a year. By 23-24, over 100 did.
  • No player from 11-12 until 14-15 averaged over 8 threes a game. In 23-24 alone, 14 did.

Centers and Power Forwards shoot well, shoot more

Since the beginning of the major three point attempt increase in the 11-12 season:¶

  • Power Forwards have increased from 10% of all threes taken to almost 18%
  • Centers have gone from almost none (about 1%) taken to 7.5%

Height and Weight are less negatively correlated with three point percentage today than in 11-12:¶

  • Correlation coefficient for player height and 3FG% went from -0.247 up to -0.116
  • Correlation coefficient for player weight and 3FG% went from -0.309 up to -0.123

Passing has evolved too

More Assists, and higher percentage of baskets are assisted¶

  • Assists have gone up from about 21 per game to over 26 per game
  • Assist percentage has also increased, from 57% to above 63%
  • Teams in 23-24 season averaged 5.13 players with 2.5+ assists per game (minimum 20 games played), compared to only 3.20 in 11-12

Assists are being spread around

Point guards are still the main assistmen, but all positions contribute¶

  • Centers have increased their percentage of total assists from 10.1% to 14.0%
  • Power forwards have increased from 11.6% of assists to 16.3%
  • Point guards have decreased from above 40% down to 31.4%
  • Shooting guard and small forwards's percents have held steady at around 22% and 16% respectively

Different style, different body

Offensive changes have shifted the physical demands of players¶

  • Players have to keep up with a faster pace as illustrated by increased shots per game
  • Players have to 'space the floor' to generate more high value three point attempts
  • All positions are more active passers

Players have thus slimmed down significantly into more lean bodys¶

  • Average BMI of players, weighted by minutes played, has decreased for all positions
  • Largest decrease has come from centers and power forwards, whose roles have changed the most

Other Player Trends

Top players play fewer minutes, but starters overall average about the same gametime¶

  • Average minutes for the top ten most utilized players decreased from 38.01 in 11-12 to 36.86 in 23-24
  • No player has played more than 38 min/game (with more than 20 games played) since 15-16
  • Starters' average minutes have held steady around 30-31 min/game for whole 2010-2024 period

Players overall are slightly younger¶

  • Average age on first day of season of all players is down from 26.55 in 11-12 to 25.76 in 23-24
  • Average age when weighted by minutes played (to control for who is actually on the court) is down less, from 26.51 to 26.14
  • Median age is down from 26 to 25

Exemplary Teams/Players

A few teams pioneered and perfected modern style, leading in 3FGA, AST, and Efficiency¶

  • Phoenix Suns from 2004-2010 and Golden State Warriors from 2014-2019 exemplified these trends.

Certain players illustrate the new player types we see in today's NBA¶

  • Big men like Nikola Jokic and Draymond Green are now top assist men, while others like Brook Lopez have become three point threats
  • Shooters such as Steph Curry and James Harden have leveraged the three point shot to become elite, efficient scorers

Ahead of Their Time - Phoenix Suns 2004-2010

Top Efficiency¶

  • Average Efficiency of 0.0806 PTS/FGA above league average (Only 27 teams have averaged better that 0.08 above league average for a single year, while the Suns held this over a six year period)

Played fast and shared the ball¶

  • Put up 3.43 more field goal attemps than league average
  • Assisted 60.3% of made field goals when league average was only 57.7%

Lots of 3s from lots of places¶

  • Averaged 22.5 three point attempts per game when league average was only 17.2
  • Averaged 5 players with 3 or more three point attempts per game, when league average was only 3 (min 20 games played)

Early version of big man offensive hub - Boris Diaw¶

  • Averaged 6.2 assists in 05-06 even though he came off the bench

Gold Standard - Golden State Warriors 2014-2019

Top Efficiency¶

  • Averaged an efficiency of 0.085 above league average, never dropping below 0.064 above league average for a single season
  • Average win percentage of 0.785 over 5 year period

Three point shooting became league standard¶

  • Averaged 30.6 3FGA per game
  • From 2014-16, the first two years of the five year period, shot 6.1 more threes than league average
  • From 2017-19, the last two years of the period, shot only 1.2 more threes than league average

Great Passing¶

  • 5.4 assists per game more than league average
  • Average of 5 different players with at least 2.5 assists (min 20 games played), while the league averagaed under 4
  • Led in assists by PF Draymond Green, with 7.15 assists per game from 15-19

Exemplary Players

Big Man Creaters¶

  • No center had averaged 6 or more assists per game until Nikola Jokic in 17-18. He has now done so in 7 straight years
  • No power forward other than Boris Diaw had averaged 6 assists until Lebron James in 12-13. Draymond Green has now done it 8 times

Shooters¶

  • No player before Steph Curry in 15-16 had averaged 10 three point attempts per game. He has now done it six times, averaging a yearly average of 28.45 points per game and 1.42 points per shot attempt
  • In five years with at least 9 three point attempts per game, James Harden averaged a yearly average of 30.94 points per game and 1.51 points per shot attempt

Adapting to the times¶

  • Center Brook Lopez never shot more than 0.2 threes per game from the 08-09 season until the 15-16 season. In every season since, he has shot at least 4 per game

Conclusion

NBA Box Score/Roster Statistics illustrate how the game has changed¶

  • Teams play faster, shoot more 3 pointers, and share the ball more
  • The search for offensive efficiency has driven this trend, and in the last few years the optimal shot selection has been reached
  • All positions contribute to shooting and assisting, with the emergence of the big man shooter/passer a pronounced change
  • Players have slimmed down to adapt to a faster pace with more floor spacing
